ðŸš€ Basic Join Questions (INNER, LEFT)
These questions focus on retrieving combined data using the most common join types.

1. INNER JOIN: List the name of every employee along with the name of the department they work in. (This is the most common use case for an INNER JOIN).
2.LEFT JOIN (A): List every department name and, if they exist, the names of the employees who work in that department. Include departments that currently have no employees.
3.LEFT JOIN (B) & Filtering: Find the names of employees who belong to the 'Sales' department and their respective salaries.

ðŸŽ¯ Advanced Join Questions (RIGHT, FULL, Self-Join)
These introduce less common joins or require joining a table to itself.

2.RIGHT JOIN: List the name of every employee and their department's location. Use a RIGHT JOIN to ensure you list all employees, even if a department ID is somehow missing in the Departments table (though this is less common than a LEFT JOIN).
3.FULL OUTER JOIN (Conceptual): List all employee names and all department names. If an employee doesn't have a department, show a NULL for the department name. If a department has no employees, show a NULL for the employee name. (Note: Not all SQL systems support FULL OUTER JOIN).
4.Multiple Joins & Aggregation: Calculate the average salary for each department. List the DepartmentName and the calculated Average Salary, ordering the result from highest to lowest average salary.

ðŸ”‘ Filtering and Analysis Questions

1.These questions require joins plus filtering (WHERE) or grouping/aggregation (GROUP BY).
2.Filtering & Join: Find the names of all employees who earn more than $60,000 and the name of their department.
3.JOIN & Finding Unmatched Data: Identify departments that currently have no employees. List only the DepartmentName. (Requires a LEFT JOIN and a check for NULL employee IDs).
4.JOIN & Subquery/CTE: Find the department with the highest average salary. (Requires calculating average salary per department and then finding the maximum).
